						</isee:model_view>
						<text_box font_size="11pt" x="517.597" y="85.3846" width="507.692" height="148">Admission for surgery from both pathways is constrained by theatre capacity. This is calculated as:

	number of planned 4-hour sessions per week * cases per session * theatre efficiency

It is also necessary to incorporate those cases that are NHS funded but carried out by independent providers. In 2025, ~33% of all NHS-funded elective hip &amp; knee replacements were carried out by independent providers.</text_box>
						<text_box font_weight="bold" font_size="16pt" x="15.1539" y="345.154" width="182.16" height="25.0769">Sub-optimal pathway</text_box>
						<text_box font_weight="bold" font_size="16pt" x="8.84611" y="105.846" width="129.083" height="49.6923">Ideal pathway (early screening)</text_box>
						<text_box font_size="11pt" x="43.0599" y="222.385" width="285.846" height="105.154">A number of cases are cancelled within 24 hours of planned surgery date. This can happen for a number of reasons, but is often due to patients not being medically fit for surgery. This is modelled by returning these patients to the sub-optimal queue of people waiting to be admitted.</text_box>
						<text_box font_size="11pt" x="367.706" y="482.179" width="514.423" height="102.996">The average length of stay until medically fit is a weighted average of LoS for the sub-optimal pathway and shortened LoS for the early screening pathway.

A proportion of medically fit patients are delayed in their discharge. Preparing for discharge earlier than at the point of admission can reduce this proportion, as can prehabilitiation, as part of the early screening process. It can also reduce the length of stay of the delay.</text_box>
					</view>
				</isee:story>
			</isee:stories>
